The Catacombs of Nightfall

Beneath Midgaard's southern chapel quarter lies a complex that began as a
sanctioned burial-adjudication institution during the city's Lantern era.
The Nightfall quarter served as a convergence point where three burdens met:
the dead who had to be named, the debts that had to be settled, and the
oaths that had to be archived.

The catacombs inherited two incompatible worldviews. From Midgaard came the
bureaucratic doctrine that order is memory made legible. From the forest
peoples came the oath doctrine that memory is relational and must remain in
living cycle. The long tragedy of Nightfall is the conversion of these
doctrines from partnership to predation.

During the Violet Compact era, the catacombs were managed through a shared
administrative apparatus that also served the Gloamvault of Kel'Shadra and
Midgaard's Dungeon. The same registry system that documented arcane materials
entering the Gloamvault also catalogued remains entering Nightfall. The same
sealed warrants that authorized prisoner transfers also authorized the
reclassification of unclaimed bodies as 'civic remainder.'

As Kel'Shadra's influence deepened, the burial halls transformed from civic
infrastructure into doctrinal territory. What had been administrative
processing of the dead became institutional control of memory itself. The
chapel quarter's bells fell silent during the same suppression cycle that
produced the Night of Unsounded Bells in the Gloamvault.

The catacombs are now connected to the broader Kel'Shadra apparatus through
passages that were never meant to be public knowledge. Those who enter find
not random haunting but procedural horror: the undead carry out functions that
once served governance, and the architecture still sorts the living as though
intake processing never ended.

The institutional memory politics of Midgaard's darkest era are literally
buried here, beneath the streets of the city that would prefer to forget.
